{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0,0.64,0.12,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97681"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12511"},{"type":"tags","id":"12609"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97681"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EImmunodeficiencies can be classified as primary (inherited) or acquired conditions that affect specific components of the immune system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pattern of infection typically seen in patients with T-cell defects?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased susceptibility to extracellular bacteria","Increased susceptibility to Neisseria species","Increased susceptibility to intracellular pathogens","Increased susceptibility to encapsulated bacteria","Increased susceptibility to pyogenic bacterial infections"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients with T-cell defects typically show \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased susceptibility to intracellular pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly viruses and some parasites. T cells are crucial for cell-mediated immunity, which is essential for controlling infections where pathogens live within host cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased susceptibility to extracellular bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of antibody deficiencies (such as X-linked agammaglobulinaemia), not T-cell defects. Antibodies are important for neutralising and opsonising extracellular pathogens like \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased susceptibility to Neisseria species\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in deficiencies of the late components of the complement cascade (C5-C9), not in T-cell defects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased susceptibility to encapsulated bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with defects in early components of the complement cascade or with antibody deficiencies, not primarily with T-cell defects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased susceptibility to pyogenic bacterial infections\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of defects in Toll-like receptor signalling pathways (such as MyD88 or IRAK4 mutations) or neutrophil function defects, not primarily T-cell defects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, specific types of T-cell defects can lead to particular infection patterns. For example, defects affecting Th1 cells (such as mutations in IL-12 or IFN-\u03b3 receptors) are associated with atypical mycobacterial infections, while defects affecting Th17 cells (such as STAT3 mutations) are associated with chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immunodeficiencies can be inherited (primary) or acquired, and they increase susceptibility to specific types of infections.","Different immune defects lead to vulnerability to particular pathogens based on which immune component is affected.","T-cell defects primarily increase susceptibility to intracellular pathogens including viruses and certain parasites."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 344-345."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80277"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-08T18:06:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-08T18:07:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13619"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97681"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T